const a = [
  {"id":14062,"text":"A 56-year-old man was taking medications for osteoporosis secondary to hyperparathyroidism and recently was diagnosed with osteosarcoma. Which of the following medications he must be using?","explanation":null,"reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Cinacalcet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Strontium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fosamax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Teriparatide","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19259,"text":"A 23-year-old woman has a routine health status examination. Her body mass index is 22. Laboratory studies show fasting plasma glucose is 120 mg/dL. Urinalysis shows mild glucosuria, but no ketonuria or proteinuria. She has no detectable insulin autoantibodies. Her father was similarly affected at age 20. She is most likely to have a mutation in a gene encoding for which of the following?","explanation":"This patient's presentation, including a family history of similar symptoms and elevated fasting plasma glucose, is indicative of a condition known as **maturity-onset diabetes of the young (MODY)**. MODY is a rare form of diabetes that typically presents in young individuals and is often misdiagnosed as type 1 or type 2 diabetes.\r\n\r\nMODY is caused by mutations in various genes, and the specific gene involved can determine the clinical characteristics. In this case, the patient is most likely to have a mutation in the gene encoding for **glucokinase**.\r\n\r\n**Glucokinase** is an enzyme that plays a crucial role in glucose metabolism by facilitating the conversion of glucose to glucose-6-phosphate in the liver and pancreatic beta cells. Mutations in the glucokinase gene lead to a reduced sensitivity of pancreatic beta cells to glucose, resulting in a higher fasting plasma glucose level without significant ketonuria or proteinuria. This form of MODY is often referred to as MODY2.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1105.","responses":[{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MHC DR","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucokinase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22236,"text":"A 42-year-old man presents with polyuria and polydipsia for the past 4 months. On physical examination, there are no specific findings. Laboratory findings include serum Na+ 155 mol/L; K+ 3.9 mol/L; Cl- 111 mmol/L; glucose 84 mg/dL; creatinine 1 mg/dL. The specific gravity of urine is 1.002 (low). Which of the following is most likely to be deficient in this patient?","explanation":"The patient's presentation of polyuria and polydipsia, along with a low urine specific gravity and hypernatremia (high serum sodium concentration), is indicative of **diabetes insipidus**, which is caused by a deficiency of **antidiuretic hormone (ADH)**. ADH, also known as vasopressin, is produced by the hypothalamus and stored and released by the posterior pituitary gland. It plays a crucial role in regulating water balance in the body by concentrating urine and reducing urine output.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nProlactin is involved in lactation and breast development.\r\nMelatonin regulates sleep-wake cycles.\r\nOxytocin is involved in childbirth and lactation.\r\nCorticotropin (ACTH) stimulates the adrenal glands to release cortisol but does not directly influence water balance or urine concentration.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1073-1074.","responses":[{"text":"Oxytocin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticotropin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antidiuretic hormone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Melatonin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22237,"text":"A 40-year-old woman notices that her gloves from the previous winter do not fit her hands. Her friends remark that her facial features have changed over the past year and that her voice seems deeper. On physical examination, . Her blood pressure is 140/90 mm Hg. She has coarse facial features. Examination of the foot shows an increased amount of soft tissue beneath the sole. Which of the following statements is more appropriate for her condition?","explanation":"This woman's symptoms – gloves not fitting, change in facial features, deepening of the voice, coarse facial features, and increased soft tissue beneath the sole – are suggestive of acromegaly. **Acromegaly** is caused by the overproduction of growth hormone (GH), usually due to a pituitary adenoma.\r\n\r\nIn acromegaly, there is a **failure of GH to suppress to normal levels in response to an oral glucose tolerance test** (OGTT), which is a key diagnostic criterion for this condition. Normally, ingestion of glucose leads to a decrease in GH levels, but in acromegaly, this suppression does not occur.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1071.","responses":[{"text":"Increased serum cortisol level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased serum TSH level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abnormal glucose tolerance test result","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Failure of growth hormone suppression","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated serum prolactin level","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22522,"text":"A middle-aged man always remains dirty. He always complains about hearing voices saying Mr. Xavier is against you. What is the false perception of something in the absence of an external stimuli known as?","explanation":"**Hallucinations** involve sensory experiences that appear real but are created by the mind. They can occur in any sensory modality, including auditory, visual, olfactory, gustatory, and tactile. In this case, the man is experiencing auditory hallucinations.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nDelusion is a strongly held false belief that is resistant to reasoning or confrontation with actual fact.\r\nGrandiosity refers to an exaggerated sense of one's importance or abilities, often seen in manic episodes or narcissistic personality disorder.\r\nBipolar disorder is a mood disorder characterized by episodes of mania and depression but is not a type of false perception.\r\nIllusion involves a distorted or misinterpreted real external stimulus, different from hallucination which does not involve any external stimuli.","reference":"Hallucinations: Definition, causes, treatment \u0026 types. (n.d.). Cleveland Clinic. Retrieved January 15, 2024, from https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/symptoms/23350-hallucinations","responses":[{"text":"Bipolar disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Grandiosity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hallucination","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Illusion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22523,"text":"Which of the following terms is used to describe a false belief that cannot be corrected?","explanation":"**Delusions** are a key symptom of various psychiatric disorders, including schizophrenia and certain mood disorders. They are **firmly held** despite clear or reasonable evidence to the contrary and are not part of the person's cultural or religious beliefs. Delusions are a feature of psychosis and can be about a variety of themes, such as persecution, grandeur, or somatic concerns.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nGrandiosity refers to an exaggerated sense of one's importance, power, knowledge, or identity, often seen in mania or narcissistic personality disorder.\r\nMania is a state of elevated mood, increased activity or energy levels, and other symptoms like rapid speech, decreased need for sleep, and impulsivity.\r\nHallucination involves perceiving something that is not present in reality, such as hearing voices or seeing things that aren't there.\r\nIllusion refers to a misperception or misinterpretation of a real external stimulus.","reference":"Kiran C, Chaudhury S. Understanding delusions. Industrial Psychiatry Journal. Published 2009. Accessed January 26, 2024. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3016695/","responses":[{"text":"Grandiosity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mania","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hallucination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Illusion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22524,"text":"While picking cotton from cotton pods, a farmer's wife develops nausea and dyspnea. When brought to the hospital, she is diagnosed with organophosphate poisoning. Which of the following is the most likely route of entry of the poison?","explanation":"The most likely route of entry of the poison in this patient is **contact with intact skin**. Organophosphates, commonly used in pesticides, can be readily absorbed through the skin, especially during activities like farming where there is direct contact with plants and soil that may be treated with these chemicals.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nContact with mucous membranes and via the eyes are potential routes, but less probable compared to dermal exposure in this scenario.\r\n\r\nGastrointestinal route would be more relevant if the toxin was ingested, which does not seem to be the case here.\r\nInhalation is also a possible route, especially if the chemicals are sprayed, but in the context of picking cotton, skin contact is more likely to be the primary route of exposure.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 596.","responses":[{"text":"Inhalation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contact with mucuous membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eyes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contact with intact skin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrointestinal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22525,"text":"To differentiate between true and feigned insanity, a medical officer will notice which of the following in a patient who is truly insane?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas, Gautam. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed., Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers, 2015: 408.","responses":[{"text":"Remains aggressive all the time","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Feels tired soon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Has facial expressions that do not match with emotions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Is abusive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Minds repeated examination","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22526,"text":"A 25-year-old man was traveling by train when he was offered a samosa with a cup of tea by a fellow passenger. After an hour he became aggressive and started talking irrelevantly and picking thread from his clothes. On examination, he was found to have dilated pupils, dysarthria, dry hot skin, and drunken gait. What is the poison responsible for this man's presentation?","explanation":"The symptoms described in the 25-year-old man - aggression, irrelevant talking, visual hallucinations (such as picking thread from clothes), dilated pupils, dysarthria (speech difficulties), dry hot skin, and a drunken gait - are characteristic of **anticholinergic poisoning**. These symptoms align with poisoning by **dhatura**, a plant that contains potent anticholinergic substances such as scopolamine and atropine.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nIce crystal (commonly a street name for methamphetamine) would more likely cause symptoms of stimulant intoxication, such as increased energy, decreased appetite, and increased alertness, rather than anticholinergic effects.\r\nAmphetamine is also a stimulant and would produce effects similar to ice crystal, not anticholinergic symptoms.\r\nCharas (cannabis resin) typically causes relaxation, euphoria, altered sensory perception, and sometimes paranoia or anxiety, not anticholinergic poisoning symptoms.\r\nOpium and its derivatives lead to opioid intoxication symptoms, such as respiratory depression, pinpoint pupils, and decreased level of consciousness, which are quite different from the presentation described.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Endocrinology-II; Subject: Forensic Medicine, Topic: Deliriant Poisons (Dhatura).","responses":[{"text":"Ice crystal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Charas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amphetamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dhatura","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Opium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22527,"text":"A 25-year-old addict was spraying insecticide in the fields for the last three hours when he suddenly developed shortness of breath and cough. On examination he was found to have miosis, lacrimation, and salivation. What is the antidote of this poison?","explanation":"The symptoms in this patient - shortness of breath, cough, miosis (constriction of the pupils), lacrimation (tearing), and salivation - are indicative of **organophosphate poisoning**, which is a common type of poisoning in agricultural settings due to exposure to certain types of insecticides. Organophosphates inhibit acetylcholinesterase, leading to an accumulation of acetylcholine and the overstimulation of muscarinic and nicotinic receptors.\r\n\r\nThe antidote for organophosphate poisoning is **atropine**. Atropine is an antimuscarinic agent that blocks the effects of acetylcholine at muscarinic receptors, helping to alleviate the muscarinic symptoms of organophosphate poisoning, such as miosis, lacrimation, and salivation. Additional treatment with pralidoxime, which reactivates acetylcholinesterase, may also be necessary for complete management of organophosphate toxicity.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nNalorphine and naloxone are opioid antagonists, used to treat opioid overdose.\r\nPhysostigmine is a cholinesterase inhibitor and would worsen organophosphate poisoning.\r\nBAL (British Anti-Lewisite) is used for heavy metal poisoning.","reference":"Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 132.","responses":[{"text":"Physostigmine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BAL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nalorphine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Naloxone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atropine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22529,"text":"A 50-year-old male patient was diagnosed as a case of hyperthyroidism and the treating physician suggested him an anti-thyroid drug. Which of the following drugs inhibits the organification step of thyroid hormone synthesis?","explanation":"**Methimazole** is an antithyroid drug that inhibits the **organification of iodide**, which is the process by which iodide is oxidized and attached to tyrosine residues in thyroglobulin to form thyroid hormones. Methimazole is actually the active metabolite of carbimazole. These medications prevent the synthesis of new thyroid hormones, which is crucial in the management of hyperthyroidism.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nIodides can inhibit several steps in the thyroid hormone synthesis process, but their primary action is not at the organification step. Thiocyanate has an antithyroid effect by inhibiting the uptake of iodine by the thyroid gland, not the organification step directly. Radioactive iodine is used in the treatment of hyperthyroidism as well, but it works by destroying thyroid tissue rather than inhibiting hormone synthesis directly.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 360.","responses":[{"text":"Carbimazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radioactive iodine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thiocynate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methimazole","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22530,"text":"A 60-year-old female with multinodular goiter is scheduled for a near total thyroidectomy. Which of the drugs will be administered for 10-14 days before surgery to reduce the vascularity of her thyroid gland?","explanation":"The use of **Lugol's solution** helps to reduce the vascularity of the thyroid gland, making the surgical procedure less risky in terms of bleeding. This preparation with iodide is known as the \"Plummer's regimen\" and is particularly useful in cases where the thyroid is highly vascular, as in multinodular goiter or Graves' disease.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nLiothyronine and Levothyroxine are thyroid hormone replacements and do not reduce vascularity of the thyroid gland.\r\nPrednisone is a corticosteroid and is not typically used to reduce thyroid vascularity.\r\nRadioactive iodine is used for the treatment of hyperthyroidism and for ablative therapy in thyroid cancer but is not used preoperatively to reduce thyroid vascularity in the context of surgery.","reference":"Katzung, B. G. (Ed.). (2018). Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology (14th ed.). McGraw-Hill Education: 318.","responses":[{"text":"Prednisone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lugol's solution","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radioactive iodine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levothyroxine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liothyronine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22709,"text":"A 40-year-old woman presents with an increasing feeling of fullness in her neck for the past 7 months. On physical examination, her thyroid gland is enlarged and nodular. A fine needle aspiration biopsy of the thyroid is done, and she undergoes thyroidectomy. Gross examination of the thyroid shows a multicentric thyroid neoplasm; microscopically, the neoplasm is composed of polygonal to spindle-shaped cells forming nests and trabeculae. There is a prominent, pink hyaline stroma. Which of the following immunohistochemical stains is most likely to be useful in the diagnosis of this neoplasm?","explanation":"The description of the thyroid neoplasm in the case - a multicentric thyroid neoplasm with polygonal to spindle-shaped cells forming nests and trabeculae, and a prominent, pink hyaline stroma - is suggestive of **medullary thyroid carcinoma** (MTC). In MTC, the neoplastic cells are derived from the parafollicular C cells of the thyroid, which produce calcitonin.\r\n\r\nTherefore, the most likely useful immunohistochemical stain in the diagnosis of this neoplasm is **calcitonin**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nCytokeratin is a marker for epithelial cells and is broadly used in differentiating carcinomas from non-epithelial tumors.\r\nParathyroid hormone (PTH) would be used in the evaluation of parathyroid lesions, not thyroid neoplasms.\r\nVimentin is a marker for mesenchymal cells and would not typically be elevated in thyroid neoplasms.\r\nCathepsin D is a lysosomal enzyme and is not a specific marker for medullary thyroid carcinoma.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1099.","responses":[{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vimentin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parathyroid hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytokeratin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cathepsin D","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22714,"text":"A 29-year-old female has a TSH of 13.5 mlU/L (normal: 0.5 to 4.7 mlU/L) Which of the following agents is most appropriate to treat this TSH abnormality?","explanation":"Elevated TSH levels typically indicate **hypothyroidism,** a condition where the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormone. **Levothyroxine** is a synthetic form of thyroxine (T4) and is the standard treatment for hypothyroidism. It helps to normalize the thyroid hormone levels, thereby reducing the TSH levels back to the normal range.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPropylthiouracil is used in the treatment of hyperthyroidism, not hypothyroidism.\r\nLiotrix is a combination of levothyroxine and liothyronine, used in some cases, but levothyroxine alone is generally preferred.\r\nLiothyronine is a synthetic form of triiodothyronine (T3) and is not typically the first-line treatment for hypothyroidism.\r\nDextrothyroxine is not used for the treatment of hypothyroidism.","reference":"Katzung, B. G. (Ed.). (2018). Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology (14th ed.). McGraw-Hill Education: 316, 318.","responses":[{"text":"Propylthiouracil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liothyronine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liotrix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levothyroxine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dextrothyroxine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22715,"text":"A 44-year-old man sees his physician because of a ''lump'' on the left side of his neck. Physical examination shows a non-tender nodule on the left lobe of the thyroid gland. A cervical node is also enlarged and non-tender. Laboratory studies show no thyroid autoantibodies in his serum, and the T4 and TSH levels are normal. A thyroidectomy is performed. Microscopic examination of the thyroid shows the features of papillary carcinoma. Which of the following is most likely to contribute to the development of the thyroid nodule in this patient?","explanation":"**Papillary thyroid carcinoma**, the most common type of thyroid cancer, is often associated with genetic mutations, including those involving the BRAF, RET/PTC, and other **tyrosine kinase receptors**. These mutations lead to uncontrolled cell growth and proliferation, contributing to the development of the carcinoma.\r\n\r\n----\r\n\r\nThere is no strong evidence linking viral infections with the development of thyroid nodules or papillary thyroid carcinoma.\r\n\r\nAdrenal medullary pheochromocytoma is a tumor of the adrenal gland and is unrelated to thyroid nodules or thyroid carcinoma.\r\n\r\nWhile iodine deficiency is associated with goiter and an increased risk for follicular thyroid cancer, it is less commonly linked with papillary thyroid carcinoma.\r\n\r\nSubstances that interfere with thyroid hormone production can lead to goiter formation, but they are not directly linked to the development of thyroid cancer, particularly papillary carcinoma.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 220, 347.","responses":[{"text":"Adrenal medullary pheochromocytoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic dietary iodine deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Consumption of goitrogens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine kinase receptor gene mutation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22717,"text":"This medication is used to treat hyperparathyroidism in patients with chronic renal failure. It works by mimicking the role of calcium in the blood and tricks the parathyroid gland into stopping the secretion of parathyroid hormone (PTH). Which of the following medications matches with this description?","explanation":"**Sensipar** is a calcimimetic agent that increases the sensitivity of the calcium-sensing receptors in the parathyroid glands, effectively reducing PTH secretion. It is used to treat hyperparathyroidism in patients with chronic renal failure and works by mimicking the role of calcium in the blood to inhibit the secretion of parathyroid hormone (PTH), \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nVasopressin is an antidiuretic hormone used in conditions like diabetes insipidus and certain cases of vasodilatory shock, not related to hyperparathyroidism.\r\nFosamax (alendronate) is a bisphosphonate used in the treatment of osteoporosis, working by inhibiting bone resorption.\r\nCalcitonin is used in conditions like osteoporosis and hypercalcemia, it lowers blood calcium levels by inhibiting osteoclast activity in bones.\r\nCarbimazole is an antithyroid medication used in the treatment of hyperthyroidism, not hyperparathyroidism.","reference":"Katzung, B. G. (Ed.). (2018). Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology (14th ed.). McGraw-Hill Education: 353.","responses":[{"text":"Fosamax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasopressin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sensipar","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbimazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22719,"text":"Which of the following is the most common side effect of insulin therapy in type 1 diabetic patients?","explanation":"The most common side effect of insulin therapy in type 1 diabetic patients is **hypoglycemia**. Insulin therapy is essential for managing blood glucose levels in type 1 diabetes. However, if insulin doses are not properly balanced with food intake and physical activity, it can lead to hypoglycemia, a condition where blood sugar levels drop too low. This can cause symptoms like dizziness, sweating, confusion, and even loss of consciousness in severe cases.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nDry cough is not a known side effect of insulin.\r\nHypertension (high blood pressure) is not typically caused by insulin.\r\nHyponatremia (low sodium levels) is also not a typical side effect of insulin therapy.\r\nPancreatitis is not commonly associated with insulin use in Type 1 diabetes.","reference":"Katzung, B. G. (Ed.). (2018). Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology (14th ed.). McGraw-Hill Education: 342.","responses":[{"text":"Dry cough","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglycemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22720,"text":"A 14-year-old boy with type 1 diabetes is brought to the hospital complaining of dizziness. Laboratory findings show severe hypoglycemia and ketoacidosis. Which of the following drugs should be administered to achieve rapid control of severe ketoacidosis?","explanation":"For rapid control of severe ketoacidosis in a patient with type 1 diabetes, the appropriate drug to administer is **regular insulin**. In diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), there is a significant deficiency of insulin leading to high blood sugar levels and the production of ketones. Regular insulin, given intravenously, is the treatment of choice in this situation because it acts quickly to lower blood glucose levels and suppress ketone production.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nTolbutamide and glyburide are oral sulfonylureas used in the treatment of Type 2 diabetes, not for rapid control of DKA in Type 1 diabetes.\r\nNPH insulin suspension is an intermediate-acting insulin, and Insulin glargine is a long-acting insulin. Both have slower onsets of action compared to regular insulin and are not suitable for the immediate management of DKA.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 314.","responses":[{"text":"Regular insulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"NPH insulin suspension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin glargine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tolbutamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glyburide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22721,"text":"A 73-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with complaints of fatigue, sluggishness, weight gain, cold intolerance, dry skin, and muscle weakness for the last 2 months. When initiating T4 therapy for an elderly patient with long standing hypothyroidism, small doses are administered in the beginning. This is done to avoid which of the following?","explanation":"When initiating T4 (levothyroxine) therapy in an elderly patient with long-standing hypothyroidism, small doses are administered initially to avoid **overstimulation of the heart**. Patients with long-standing hypothyroidism, especially the elderly, can have reduced cardiac reserve. Sudden increases in metabolism and cardiac demand due to rapid correction of hypothyroidism with high doses of levothyroxine can lead to cardiac complications, including angina, arrhythmias, and even myocardial infarction.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nA flare-up of exophthalmus is typically associated with hyperthyroidism (Graves' disease), not the treatment of hypothyroidism.\r\nAcute renal failure is not a typical concern when starting T4 therapy in hypothyroidism.\r\nSeizures and hemolysis are not standard complications associated with the initiation of levothyroxine therapy in hypothyroidism.","reference":"Katzung, B. G. (Ed.). (2018). Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology (14th ed.). McGraw-Hill Education: 318.","responses":[{"text":"Seizures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overstimulation of the heart","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A flare-up of exopthalmus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22941,"text":"A professor wants to award a prize to his students on their remarkable performance in the exam. There were five students who are tied for the first position while the professor had to choose only one student among the 5. Which of the following would be a fair technique, which will help the professor choose one out of the five eligible students?","explanation":"The fairest technique for the professor to choose one student out of the five who are tied for the first position would be **simple random sampling**. This method ensures that every student has an equal chance of being selected. The professor could use various methods such as drawing names from a hat, using a random number generator, or rolling a fair die if it is numbered for the five students.\r\n\r\nQuota sampling involves selecting people to represent certain characteristics proportionally, which is not applicable here. Convenience sampling involves choosing individuals who are easiest to reach, which would not be fair in this scenario. Consecutive sampling involves selecting every subject that meets the criteria in order, which would not allow for a random choice in this case. Stratified random sampling involves dividing the population into strata and randomly sampling from each stratum, which is not necessary since all students are already tied for first place and are considered a homogeneous group for the purpose of the prize selection.","reference":"Elfil M, Negida A. Sampling methods in clinical research; an educational review. Emerg (Tehran). 2017;5(1):e52. Accessed January 26, 2024. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5325924/","responses":[{"text":"Convenience sampling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified random sampling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quota sampling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple random sampling","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Consecutive sampling","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22942,"text":"A researcher wants to select an unbiased sample, which will account for the various ethnicities residing in the area. Which of the following techniques will help the professor to recruit such a sample?","explanation":"For recruiting a sample that represents various ethnicities residing in an area, the most appropriate technique would be **stratified random sampling**. This method involves dividing the population into separate groups, or strata, based on ethnicity. A random sample is then taken from each stratum proportional to the stratum's size in the population or equal numbers from each stratum, depending on the research goal.\r\n\r\nSystematic random sampling involves selecting members of a population at a regular interval after a random start, which doesn't guarantee proportional representation of all ethnicities. Quota sampling could ensure representation but is not random as it involves selecting a specific number of participants from each ethnicity until the quota is met, which could introduce selection bias. Simple random sampling does not ensure that all ethnic groups will be proportionately represented. Consecutive sampling involves taking every subject that meets the criteria consecutively until the sample size is met, which may not consider ethnic variability.","reference":"Elfil M, Negida A. Sampling methods in clinical research; an educational review. Emerg (Tehran). 2017;5(1):e52. Accessed January 26, 2024. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5325924/","responses":[{"text":"Simple random sampling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic random sampling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quota sampling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified random sampling","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Consecutive sampling","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22943,"text":"A professor was giving a lecture on the significance of sample size estimation. He emphasized that a large sample size will help to find whether the difference between two or more groups exists in reality. Which of the following was the professor referring to?","explanation":"**Power** is the probability that a study will detect a real difference between two or more groups if a difference truly exists. A larger sample size increases the statistical power of a study, which means it reduces the likelihood of committing a type II error (failing to reject a false null hypothesis). In other words, a study with sufficient power is more likely to correctly identify a true effect.\r\n\r\nType I error (or alpha error) is the probability of rejecting a true null hypothesis, falsely claiming that there is an effect when there isn't one. Confidence intervals are a range of values that estimate the true value of a parameter with a certain degree of confidence. The p-value indicates the probability of obtaining the observed results, or more extreme results, if the null hypothesis were true.","reference":"Mascha EJ, Vetter TR. Significance, errors, power, and sample size: the blocking and tackling of statistics. Anesthesia and Analgesia. Published February 2018. Accessed January 1, 2024. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29346210/","responses":[{"text":"Power","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha error","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 error","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"P-value","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confidence interval","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22944,"text":"A researcher wants to select an unbiased national-level sample, which will account for the various ethnicities residing in Pakistan. He received a milllion dollar grant to find out the prevalence of hemoglobinopathies in Pakistan. Which of the following techniques will help the professor recruit such a sample?","explanation":"To select an unbiased national-level sample that accounts for the various ethnicities residing in Pakistan and aims to find out the prevalence of hemoglobinopathies, the researcher should use **cluster sampling**. This method involves dividing the population into clusters that represent the population as a whole. In this case, clusters could be based on geographical regions, cities, or districts, each of which likely contains a mix of the various ethnicities present in Pakistan. Then a random sample of clusters is selected, and all or a random sample of individuals within these clusters are included in the study.\r\n\r\nConvenience sampling would involve selecting individuals who are easiest to reach, which could introduce bias. Consecutive sampling involves selecting every subject that meets the criteria consecutively until the sample size is met and may not accurately represent all ethnicities. Purposive sampling involves selecting a specific subgroup of interest, which may not be representative of the national population. Quota sampling ensures representation of certain characteristics but does not necessarily provide a random or unbiased national-level sample.","reference":"Elfil M, Negida A. Sampling methods in clinical research; an educational review. Emerg (Tehran). 2017;5(1):e52. Accessed January 26, 2024. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5325924/","responses":[{"text":"Cluster sampling","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Purposive sampling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Consecutive sampling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quota sampling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Convenience sampling","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22945,"text":"A group of medical students submits the plan for their research project to the institutional board. This plan contains background, objectives, hypothesis, methodology, consent form, questionnaire, and references. Which of the following best defines this plan for research given in the above scenario?","explanation":"A **synopsis** is a brief summary or general overview of an entire project. It typically outlines the main elements of a research project, including its purpose and how the research will be conducted, which is what the students have provided.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAn abstract is a short summary of a research article, thesis, review, or other in-depth analysis and is typically only a paragraph long. The rationale explains the reasoning behind the choice of the study and its design. An introduction is the first section of a research paper or project that sets the stage and provides context but does not usually include detailed methodology or instruments like consent forms and questionnaires. The hypothesis is a specific statement of prediction that the study aims to test, and while it is a part of the students' plan, it does not describe the entire plan.","reference":"Sudheesh K, Duggappa DR, Nethra SS. How to write a research proposal? Indian Journal of Anaesthesia. Published September 2016. Accessed January 1, 2024. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27729688/","responses":[{"text":"Synopsis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rationale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Introduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abstract","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22946,"text":"A group of researchers write a research proposal and in it they gave an explanation of the fundamental reasons for their research. Which of the following best describes the justification of the research work?","explanation":null,"reference":"Al-Riyami A. How to prepare a research proposal. Oman Med J. 2008;23(2):66-69. Accessed January 25, 2024. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3282423/","responses":[{"text":"Operational definition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rationale","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Objective","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Introduction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22948,"text":"A 6-month-old infant is brought to the outpatient department with by his parents with concerns about his general health. According to them, he was born at term at home with good weight and length but had a history of prolonged jaundice. Now they feel he is not active; he sleeps more and feeds less. There is also a history of constipation. On examination, the anterior fontanelle is open and large and the posterior fontanelle is still open. Which is the most likely investigation that will help in the diagnosis?","explanation":"The clinical presentation suggests the possibility of **congenital hypothyroidism**. In infants with congenital hypothyroidism, there may be delayed closure of the fontanelles (particularly the anterior fontanelle), poor feeding, constipation, jaundice, and decreased activity. Thyroid hormone is essential for normal growth and development, including brain development, and congenital hypothyroidism can lead to developmental delays if left untreated.\r\n\r\nTesting the **TSH level** is a common screening method for congenital hypothyroidism. Elevated TSH levels with low levels of thyroid hormones (T4) are indicative of hypothyroidism. Early diagnosis and treatment of congenital hypothyroidism are critical to prevent developmental and cognitive impairment. Therefore, measuring the TSH level is essential to assess the thyroid function in this infant.","reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2018: 455.","responses":[{"text":"Karyotyping","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total bilirubin level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin-like growth factor level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"TSH level","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22990,"text":"A 13-year-old girl presented with her parents with complaints of rapid decreased in her weight. According to the parents she has also complain of tremulousness, headache, mood disturbances, behavioral swings, difficulties with sleep, decrease in attention span, hyperactivity and a decline in school performance. On examination her eyes are protruded with lid lag. Her skin is smooth and flushed with excessive sweating. She is tachycardic with increased systolic blood pressure and a widened pulse pressure. What should be the treatment of choice to treat her underlying condition?","explanation":"This child with rapid weight loss despite possible normal or increased appetite, tremulousness, headache, mood disturbances, behavioral swings, difficulty with sleep, decreased attention span, hyperactivity, decline in school performance, protruding eyes (exophthalmos) with lid lag, smooth and flushed skin with excessive sweating, tachycardia, increased systolic blood pressure, and widened pulse pressure most likely has **Graves' disease.**\r\n\r\nGraves' disease is an autoimmune disorder characterized by the overproduction of thyroid hormones (thyrotoxicosis), which leads to the signs and symptoms of hyperthyroidism. The treatment of choice in children and adolescents often starts with **antithyroid medications** that inhibit the synthesis of thyroid hormones.\r\n\r\n**Methimazole** is often the first-line treatment for pediatric Graves' disease due to its efficacy and fewer side effects compared to propylthiouracil (PTU).\r\n\r\nRadioiodine ablation is a definitive treatment for hyperthyroidism and may be considered for older adolescents and adults but is used less frequently in young children due to concerns about long-term effects, including the risk of causing hypothyroidism and the theoretical risk of cancer.\r\n\r\nNear-total thyroidectomy may be considered in cases where antithyroid drugs are not effective or not tolerated, or when there is a large goiter causing compressive symptoms. Surgery is less commonly used as the initial treatment in children.\r\n\r\nBeta blockers such as propranolol can be used to control the symptoms of hyperthyroidism like tachycardia and tremors but do not address the overproduction of thyroid hormones","reference":"Lee HS, Hwang JS. The treatment of Graves’ disease in children and adolescents. Annals of Pediatric Endocrinology \u0026 Metabolism. Published September 2014. Accessed January 21, 2024. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4208256/","responses":[{"text":"Methimazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radioiodine ablation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propylthiouracil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Near-total thyroidectomy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22992,"text":"During embryogenesis of the pituitary gland, Rathke's pouch will lead to the formation of which of the following structures of the pituitary gland?","explanation":"During embryonic development, **Rathke's pouch** is an invagination of the oral ectoderm that forms the anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis). The **pars distalis** is the largest and most functionally significant part of the anterior pituitary and arises from the proliferation of Rathke's pouch cells. It is responsible for producing several key hormones, including growth hormone (GH), prolactin (PRL), thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH), and luteinizing hormone (LH).","reference":"Ilahi S, Ilahi TB. Anatomy, adenohypophysis (Pars anterior, anterior pituitary). In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2024. Accessed January 25, 2024. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519039/","responses":[{"text":"Pars distalis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars nervosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars intermedia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Floor of third ventricle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22994,"text":"A 30-year-old woman complains of increasing weight gain, fatigability, depression and poor memory for last three months. She is noticed to have a pale complexion, dry scaly skin and high blood pressure. What is the most important investigation you will advise?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 655-657.","responses":[{"text":"Electrocardiogram","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver function tests (LFTs)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fasting lipid profile","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid stimulating hormone","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22995,"text":"In case of untreated, primary hypothyroidism, the thyroid function tests best correspond to which of the following?","explanation":"In primary hypothyroidism, the thyroid gland itself is underactive and does not produce enough thyroid hormones (T4 and T3). The pituitary gland responds to this low hormone level by increasing the production of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) in an attempt to stimulate the thyroid to produce more hormones. Therefore, a typical thyroid function test result in untreated primary hypothyroidism would show decreased levels of **free T4 (and possibly T3) and an increased level of TSH**.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 657.","responses":[{"text":"Increased free T4, Decreased TSH, Increased T3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased free T4, Decreased TSH, Decreased T3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased free T4, Increased TSH, Decreased T3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased free T4, Increased TSH, Increased reversed T3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased free T4, Decreased or normal TSH, Decreased T3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22996,"text":"When considering thyroid hormone replacement in case of primary hypothyroidism, which of the following precautions should be remembered?","explanation":"**Levothyroxine**, the standard form of thyroxine used for thyroid hormone replacement, should ideally be taken on an empty stomach to maximize its absorption. It is generally recommended to take the medication at least 30 to 60 minutes before breakfast or any other meals. Food can interfere with the medication's absorption, so taking it on an empty stomach ensures more consistent thyroid levels and better management of hypothyroidism.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThyroid hormone replacement is typically a lifelong therapy, not just for three months.\r\n\r\nThyroxine should not be stopped once a person becomes euthyroid; it is usually a continuous treatment to maintain euthyroid status.\r\n\r\nElderly people or those with heart disease often need to be started on lower, not higher, doses of thyroxine due to the potential for thyroxine to exacerbate underlying heart conditions. The dose is then gradually increased as needed and tolerated.","reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 657-658.\r\n\r\n(2) Ala S, Akha O, Kashi Z, Asgari H, Bahar A, Sasanpour N. Dose administration time from before breakfast to before dinner affect thyroid hormone levels? Caspian J Intern Med. 2015;6(3):134-140. Accessed January 21, 2024. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4650787/","responses":[{"text":"Thyroxine should be stopped as soon as person becomes euthyroid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid hormone needs to be replaced for three months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroxine tablet needs to be taken empty stomach in the morning","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Elderly people should be started at a higher doses of thyroxine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid hormone pill should be taken with breakfast","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22997,"text":"A 66-year-old woman is complaining of abdominal pain, constipation and polyuria. In the past, she underwent renal stone surgery. On examination, her blood pressure is 145/77mmHg and pulse is 98/min. Her fasting glucose and kidney function are normal but her calcium is found to be elevated at 13.05 mg/dL (NR 8.5-11.0). What is the most likely cause of her symptoms?","explanation":"**Primary hyperparathyroidism** is characterized by excessive secretion of parathyroid hormone (PTH) from the parathyroid glands, which leads to the mobilization of calcium from bones, increased intestinal absorption of calcium, and increased renal reabsorption of calcium, resulting in hypercalcemia. The symptoms of hypercalcemia include abdominal pain, constipation, and polyuria. A history of renal stones is also consistent with **hypercalcemia**, which can be a consequence of primary hyperparathyroidism. Elevated blood pressure can also be associated with hypercalcemia. The normal fasting glucose and kidney function help to rule out diabetes and chronic kidney disease, which can also affect calcium levels.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 676-678.","responses":[{"text":"Hyperthyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin D intoxication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone excess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary hyperparathyrodism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Use of thiazide diuretics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22998,"text":"A 26-year-old woman is complaining of abnormal tingling sensation in her hands and feet. For the last 2 years, a neurologist has been treating her for seizure disorder. On, examination, her blood pressure is 125/77mmHg and pulse is 98/min. Her investigations show: Calcium= 6.5 (7.5-8.5 mg/dl)\r\nPhosphate = 4.8 (2.5-4.0 mg/dl). What investigation will you do?","explanation":"The patient is presenting with **hypocalcemia**, indicated by a low calcium level, and hyperphosphatemia, indicated by a high phosphate level. This combination of electrolyte disturbances can lead to symptoms such as tingling sensations in the hands and feet, which are often associated with hypocalcemia. Given that this patient has been treated for a **seizure disorder**, it's important to consider whether the seizure medication (such as phenytoin) could be affecting her calcium levels. However, the elevated phosphate level suggests a possible parathyroid gland disorder, where PTH (parathyroid hormone) regulation is impaired. Measuring serum PTH will help determine whether the patient has **hypoparathyroidism**, which could explain both the hypocalcemia and the seizure disorder.","reference":"Rao MN, Shoback DM. Hypocalcemia. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., eds. Endotext. MDText.com, Inc.; 2000. Accessed January 21, 2024. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK344077/","responses":[{"text":"Serum albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum parathyroid hormone levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin D levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum phenytoin levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI brain","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22999,"text":"A 40-year-old female with occasional complaints of dysuria and polyuria, presents with body aches and fatigue and the following labs: PTH 103 pg/ml (10-65), Ca 8.2 mg/dl (8.5-10.0), Phosphate 4.0 mmol/L (2.5-5.0), Albumin 4.4 mg/dl (2.5-5.5), Alkaline phosphatase 243 mg/dl (\u003c 125), Vitamin D 8.0 ng/mL (\u003e 30), 1,25 hydroxyvitamin D 7.0 pg/ml (18-78). What is the most likely cause of her condition?","explanation":"**Secondary hyperparathyroidism** is characterized by an overproduction of parathyroid hormone (PTH) by the parathyroid glands in response to low calcium levels. In this case, the patient's calcium level is on the lower end of the normal range (hypocalcemia), while her PTH level is elevated, which is indicative of secondary hyperparathyroidism. Additionally, the patient has a low vitamin D level, which can lead to decreased calcium absorption and contribute to secondary hyperparathyroidism. The elevated alkaline phosphatase can be associated with bone turnover seen in this condition. Secondary hyperparathyroidism often occurs in response to chronic kidney disease, vitamin D deficiency, or other conditions that cause chronic hypocalcemia, leading to compensatory hypersecretion of PTH.","reference":"Jameson JL, Fauci AS, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Longo DL, Loscalzo J, eds. Harrison’s Principles of Internal Medicine. 20th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 2933.","responses":[{"text":"Primary hyperparathyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin D deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary hyperparathyroidism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignancy associated hypercalcemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":23000,"text":"A 30-year-old woman presents to the outpatient clinic with palpitations, weight loss and excessive sweating for almost 5-6 months. She cannot concentrate on carrying out her daily activities especially looking after her children. Recently, she has also developed pain in both eyes and her friend told her that one of her eyes has become more prominent than the other. What is the most likely cause of her condition?","explanation":"**Graves' disease** is an autoimmune disorder that is the most common cause of hyperthyroidism. It is characterized by the overproduction of thyroid hormones. The symptoms in this patient, such as palpitations, weight loss, and excessive sweating, are typical of hyperthyroidism. The additional description of eye pain and one eye becoming more prominent, also known as **exophthalmos,** is a classic sign of **Graves' ophthalmopathy**, which is a distinctive feature of Graves' disease. This combination of systemic symptoms of hyperthyroidism and eye involvement points towards Graves' disease as the most likely diagnosis.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 660-662.","responses":[{"text":"Hashimoto thyroiditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Graves' disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Toxic nodular goiter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperthyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Generalized anxiety disorder","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":23001,"text":"A 22-year-old male presents to the clinic with weight loss, diarrhea, and tremors for 2 months. He complains of excessive sweating and palpitations whenever he commutes to his office in the morning. He smokes 1 pack of cigarettes per day. He later suffers from Hashimoto's thyroiditis. His primary physician orders the following labs and refers him to you. TSH: 0.002 mIU/L (0.4-2). Serum T4: 23.8 ng/ml (6.5-11.5). What is the interpretation of his lab results?","explanation":"**Thyrotoxicosis** refers to the clinical syndrome caused by an excess of thyroid hormones, which can arise from various conditions, including Graves' disease, toxic multinodular goiter, or thyroiditis. The lab results show a significantly suppressed TSH level and a very high serum T4 level, both of which are indicative of an overactive thyroid, or hyperthyroidism. The presence of symptoms like weight loss, diarrhea, tremors, excessive sweating, and palpitations further corroborates the diagnosis of thyrotoxicosis. Hashimoto's thyroiditis can sometimes lead to a transient phase of hyperthyroidism due to the release of preformed thyroid hormones from the damaged gland, although it is typically characterized by hypothyroidism in its chronic phase.","reference":"Quintero BM, Yazbeck C, Sweeney LB. Thyroiditis: evaluation and treatment. AFP. 2021;104(6):609-617. Accessed January 21, 2024. https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2021/1200/p609.html","responses":[{"text":"Multinodular goiter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overt hyperthyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overt hypothyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodine toxicity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyrotoxicosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":23010,"text":"A 27-year-old female undergoes total thyroidectomy for multinodular goiter. During this operation, the inferior thyroid artery is ligated. Which of the following nerves is intimately related to this artery?","explanation":"The **recurrent laryngeal nerve** is closely associated with the **inferior thyroid artery.** During thyroid surgery, it is important to identify and preserve the recurrent laryngeal nerve to prevent vocal cord paralysis. The nerve courses in the tracheoesophageal groove and can be found near the inferior thyroid artery, which supplies the thyroid gland. Injury to this nerve can result in hoarseness, loss of voice, or difficulty breathing, making it a critical consideration during thyroidectomy procedures.","reference":"White AM, Lasrado S. Anatomy, head and neck, thyroid arteries. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed January 20, 2024. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560666/","responses":[{"text":"Superior laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recurrent laryngeal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"External laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a